      "body": "### Document, that, if the user calls some built-in nonce/ecdh-hash/... function manually, then it won't use the SHA256 override \n \nOr do something else, e.g., come up with a better API\n\nFrom [IRC today](https://gnusha.org/secp256k1/2026-03-09.log):\n```\n08:12 < real_or_random> one thing I wasn't fully aware of when introducing the SHA runtime override is that it doesn't work where the user can provide a function\n08:12 < real_or_random> e.g., nonce derivation or hashing the ECDH raw secret\n08:12 < sipa> right, only the internal variants get to make use of the context-dependent SHA override\n08:13 < real_or_random> noticed that in https://github.com/bitcoin-core/secp256k1/pull/1806#issuecomment-4022837213\n08:13 < real_or_random> I'm not sure if there could be a better API design. but it's not trivial, also if we want to keep it backwards compatible\n08:14 < sipa> does that mean we want to introduce a new generation of these functions, which take a new function pointer type, which receives the sha update pointer (or even just the context, and we expose a \"do hash updating with this context\")\n08:14 < sipa> i don't think we can retrofit this into the current API, it needs new functions\n08:15 < real_or_random> sipa: at the moment, even the built-in variants don't get the override. we can't really check if the user happens to provide a pointer to a built-in function\n08:15 < sipa> i think that's what the code does?\n08:16 < real_or_random> you're saying we check for  NULL?\n08:16 < real_or_random> i.e., if the function ptr is NULL\n08:16 < sipa> https://github.com/bitcoin-core/secp256k1/blob/master/src/modules/ellswift/main_impl.h#L565L572\n08:17 < sipa> are you talking about something else?\n08:17 < real_or_random> no, I think I was simply mistaken\n08:18 < real_or_random> the one in ellswift is a bit different. it doesn't have a \"NULL\" default value  \n08:18 < real_or_random> but yes, we compare function pointers\n08:18 < sipa> it's effectively implementing a translation table, which for a few well-defined common functions actually invokes an internal different one that is context-aware\n08:19 < real_or_random> in the other instances we also compare to NULL https://github.com/bitcoin-core/secp256k1/blob/1aafe15139976b0142d791aaf4963de3fc1ff736/src/modules/schnorrsig/main_impl.h#L152-L157\n08:19 < real_or_random> yes, indeed.\n08:21 < real_or_random> I think that's pragmatic given the current API, but it feels a bit awkward. if you pass, for whatever reason, a simple wrapper instead of the original function pointer, you suddenly get different performance. and different illegal/error callbacks.   \n08:21 < sipa> yup\n08:22 < real_or_random> I don't know. I'll think a bit more about it, but my feeling is that it's probably good enough now that we have this API\n08:23 < real_or_random> maybe it should be noted somewhere in the docs that the override isn't always active\n08:24 < real_or_random> I believe a simpler API would just have a different API function for each built-in way of hashing, e.g., have secp256k1_ellswift_xdh_bip324 and secp256k1_ellswift_xdh_prefix\n08:25 < real_or_random> and secp256k1_ellswift_xdh could remain an advanced API function that takes a function pointer  \n08:25 < sipa> hmm, yes, indeed\n08:26 < real_or_random> this would avoid having two generations of user-provided functions (or the breakage that comes with them) \n08:26 < real_or_random> but still not sure if it's worth the hassle \n08:26 < sipa> indeed, i think what we have is good enough in practice\n08:26 < real_or_random> we have a similar thing already in the schnorrsig module, where we have a simple and an advanced signing function\n08:27 < sipa> it doesn't scale well if we had tons of built-in functions we'd want to optimize\n08:27 < real_or_random> yeah but I believe 99% of users call it with the default\n08:27 < sipa> indeed, or one of the defaults\n08:28 < real_or_random> and the other 1% is people who want the raw ECDH secret and they don't need SHA256 anyway\n08:29 < real_or_random> may still be nice to document the status quo. I think I'll open a \"follow-ups\" issue that also mentions the other two things I brought up in #1777, so we can keep track of it\n```",
